2.  Below are detailed terms of references for three individual consultants:  

3.  Tax audit and project management expert (1 international, 10 person-months).The tax 
audit and project management expert will support MIRA’s Audit and Assessment Section in 
implementing  new  taxes  such  as the  tourism  goods  and  services  tax  (TGST),  goods  and 
services tax (GST), business profit tax (BPT), corporate profit tax (CPT), and personal income 
tax (PIT). The expert should be a tax auditor by profession and have at least 10 years of 
relevant experience as well as effective verbal and written communication skills. The expert will: 

(i)  lead, supervise, and manage MIRA’s audit and assessment section; 
(ii)  design audit strategies and develop tax audit manuals; 
(iii)  determine the nature, scope, and direction of required audits and investigations; 
(iv)  plan, review, and finalize audit engagements and review reports on audit findings; 
(v)  ensure that the tax audits are conducted in accordance with the audit plan and 
strategies and with the relevant laws and regulations of the Maldives; 
(vi)  review the tax returns, financial statements, and other records, using accepted 
accounting standards to determine taxpayers’ liability; 
(vii)  establish  a  risk-profiling  mechanism  for  how  taxpayers  will  be  selected  and 
audited. Develop, in coordination with information and communication technology 
(ICT) staff, a business requirement for interfacing the MIRA taxpayer database 
with  external  database(s)  to  support  data  cross-referencing  for  tax-audit 
purposes and a program to facilitate risk-based tax audits; 
(viii)  design  and  conduct  workshops  to  provide  dedicated  training  to  audit  and 
assessment section staff on tax-audit techniques; 
(ix)  train audit and assessment section staff in implementing audit strategies for desk 
and field audits; 
(x)  provide on-the-job mentoring for the audit and assessment section; 
(xi)  review tax legislations to identify inconsistencies and loopholes and advise on 
any rationalization deemed necessary; 
(xii)  provide technical advice on work performed by the audit and assessment section; 
(xiii)  assist  in  review  and  finalization  of  functional  and  technical  requirements  for 
introducing  an  internally  acceptable  tax-filing  system  prepared  by  the 
implementation partner in consultation with the tax information technology expert; 
(xiv)  review the training and change-management plan; 
(xv)  review  all  project-related  documents  (business  rules,  workflows,  test  scripts, 
procurement documents) prepared by MIRA, and provide feedback; 
(xvi)  monitor project risk throughout the project’s life-cycle (project preparation, blue 
printing, testing, procurement, user training, “Go-Live,” and post-implementation); 
(xvii)  provide quality control and review all the deliverables of the internet protocol to 
ensure adequate and timely implementation;  
(xviii)  provide  a  review  on  the  sustainability  of  RAMIS  once  it  is  installed  and 
operationalized; 
(xix)  carry out post-implementation analysis to understand the information exchange 
or  integration  requirements  of  RAMIS  with  various  other  departmental 
applications to move toward integrated financial management, in consultation 
with the tax ICT expert; 
(xx)  conduct training and public-awareness programs in consultation with MIRA; and
